				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p({\mathrm{TA}} \to {\mathrm{GA}}) \cdot p({\mathrm{GA}} \to {\mathrm{GC}}) \, + p({\mathrm{TA}} \to {\mathrm{TC}}) \cdot p({\mathrm{TC}} \to {\mathrm{GC}})$$\end{document}p(TA→GA)⋅p(GA→GC)+p(TA→TC)⋅p(TC→GC). Former equation involves the product of transition at CpG, while both term of the latter are product of transversion at non-CpG, which works as a reasonable explanation of the frequency difference of those two MNV patterns.

Using the same principle (and accounting for reference base pair frequency, population number and global SNV mutation rate defined by 3 bp context26, we first constructed a null model of MNV distribution. In reality, this null model does not represent the real distribution we observe, due to biological mechanisms that introduce MNV. Therefore, we allowed additional factor q, that denotes the mutational event where two SNVs are introduced at the same time. For the example of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
